[assistant] Fixed the reported failure cause in `tests/src/ant/ant/1.6/build.gradle`.
[assistant] 
[assistant] The previous setup appended only `ant-1.6.jar` to the boot classpath. That made `org.apache.tools.ant.Main` load from the bootstrap loader, but its interface `org.apache.tools.ant.launch.AntMain` lives in `ant-launcher`, which was still only on the application classpath. Gradle/JUnit then failed while discovering `MainTest$ExposedMain` with:
[assistant] 
[assistant] ```text
[assistant] NoClassDefFoundError: org/apache/tools/ant/launch/AntMain
[assistant] ```
[assistant] 
[assistant] Change made:
[assistant] 
[assistant] - Instead of appending only the main `ant` JAR, the test JVM now appends all Ant runtime JARs whose names start with `ant-` to `-Xbootclasspath/a`.
[assistant] 
[assistant] Current bootclasspath setup:
[assistant] 
[assistant] ```groovy
[assistant] tasks.withType(Test).configureEach {
[assistant]     doFirst {
[assistant]         Set<File> antJars = configurations.testRuntimeClasspath.files.findAll {
[assistant]             it.name == "ant-${libraryVersion}.jar"
[assistant]                     || it.name.startsWith("ant-")
[assistant]         }
[assistant]         if (antJars.isEmpty()) {
[assistant]             throw new GradleException(
[assistant]                     "Could not locate Ant JARs on the test runtime classpath")
[assistant]         }
[assistant]         jvmArgs "-Xbootclasspath/a:${antJars*.absolutePath.join(File.pathSeparator)}"
[assistant]     }
[assistant] }
[assistant] ```
[assistant] 
[assistant] This keeps `Available` bootstrap-loaded for the fallback branches while also making Ant’s companion artifacts, including `ant-launcher`, visible to the bootstrap loader. I did not run the test command.
